urn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n\n### 2. Review Sharing\n\nReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\nbehind a branc\n[TRUNCATED]\n even\n  when only one is relevant to the session\n\nDo not store a separate `checked_out_refs` field. It duplicates the stack/branch\nsnapshot and creates reader precedence questions. Also do not store graph\nprojection internals such as `is_entrypoint`; that is a traversal detail, not\ndurable product evidence for association.\n\nBranch names, relative file paths, review identifiers, change ids, commit ids,\nand commit file lists are acceptable for repo-scoped `gitbutler:*` metadata\nbecause they travel within the same repository metadata access boundary as the\ncode. Do not store absolute paths. Re-check this assumption before exposing the\nsame metadata in product surfaces with a narrower audience than repository\naccess, such as selected web review links.\n\nFor file paths, store relative paths plainly on the turn snapshot. They are\nimportant evidence and keep explanations understandable. The normal case should\nnot be expensive. Guard only against pathological cases such as mass renames,\ngenerated trees, vendor drops, or giant lockfile-driven commits by storing a\ncount and truncated flag alongside a capped sorted path list.\n\nUse a path cap of 256 entries per path list. Keep the total count even when the\nlist is not truncated. It is redundant in the common case, but useful for\nconsistent reads and essential when `*_truncated = true`.\n\nExample worktree shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"files\": [\"src/foo.rs\", \"src/bar.rs\"],\n  \"file_count\": 2,\n  \"files_truncated\": false\n}\n```\n\nCommit file lists should use the same pattern:\n\n```json\n{\n  \